{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501016"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:21:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:21:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1707"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1707"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.19,0.04,0.12,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98510"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1707"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80939"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2401"},{"type":"tags","id":"2446"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9099"},{"type":"tags","id":"9100"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33783"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98510"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of severe, constant and generalised abdominal pain. She has never had pain like this before. She has a medical history of hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia and atrial fibrillation. Her regular medications are perindopril and apixaban.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min and irregular, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. She has widespread abdominal tenderness, but firm pressure does not produce undue discomfort. Investigations reveal a serum amylase of 280 U/L (25-125) and serum lactate of 1.8 mmol/L (0.5-2.0). A CT scan is performed and a representative view is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most suggestive of a diagnosis of intestinal ischaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The abdominal examination findings","The irregular pulse","The serum amylase result","The serum lactate result","The CT findings"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhile there are several possible explanations for the current clinical picture, the \u003Cstrong\u003ECT findings\u003C/strong\u003E provide the most definitive diagnosis (Image). There is ascites (upper arrow) and gas visible in the portal venous system (lower arrow). Gas in the portal venous system can be distinguished from pneumobilia as the former can be seen extending right to the liver capsule, while biliary gas usually does not extend closer than 1 cm to the surface. This observation of gas in the portal venous system is virtually pathognomonic of intestinal ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal examination findings\u003C/strong\u003E of widespread tenderness without severe pain on firm pressure are consistent with intestinal ischaemia but are not specific. This pattern can be seen in other conditions such as gastroenteritis or early appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eirregular pulse\u003C/strong\u003E suggests atrial fibrillation, which is a risk factor for mesenteric ischaemia due to embolism. However, it is not diagnostic of intestinal ischaemia itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn elevated \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum amylase\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen in intestinal ischaemia, but it is neither sensitive nor specific. It can also be elevated in conditions such as pancreatitis, perforated peptic ulcer, or intestinal obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum lactate\u003C/strong\u003E is frequently used as an indicator of an ischaemic process, it has relatively poor specificity as a biomarker of intestinal ischaemia. Serum lactate values often increase in other conditions, such as gut perforation, pancreatitis, appendicitis, diabetic ketoacidosis, and malignancy. In this case, the lactate is on  the higher end of normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT imaging is the most specific diagnostic tool for mesenteric ischaemia. The presence of gas in the portal venous system, along with other findings such as bowel wall thickening, mesenteric stranding, or lack of bowel wall enhancement, strongly supports the diagnosis of intestinal ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gas in the portal venous system is almost pathognomonic  of intestinal ischaemia.","CT imaging is the most specific diagnostic tool for mesenteric ischaemia.","Serum lactate has poor specificity as a biomarker for intestinal ischaemia."],"references":["Abboud B, El Hachem J, YazbeckT, et al. Hepatic portal venous gas: Physiopathology, etiology, prognosis and treatment. World J Gastroenterol 2009; 15:3585-90. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19653334/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80939"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1707"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16850"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16851"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16850","links":{"self":"